rules_version = '2';

// Blob storage for attachments. Blobs are written at `{entityScope}/blobs/{blobId}`, so an
// attachment on aircraft `acId` owned by `uid` lands at `users/{uid}/aircraft/{acId}/blobs/...`.
//
// **Strictly user-scoped, and deliberately so.** Unlike Firestore, these rules grant nothing across
// accounts: sharing an aircraft does NOT share its attachment blobs. A member of a shared aircraft
// can read the record data (Firestore, via the aircraft_shares ACL) but not the files hanging off
// it — they are in the host's tree, and this rule denies them.
//
// That is the v1 position from design §9, not an oversight: giving members blob access needs Storage
// rules that can consult the share ACL, and Storage rules cannot `get()` Firestore. Doing it
// properly means custom claims or a token-minting function, which is the attachments-on-shared
// fast-follow. Until then the client degrades honestly — a member sees the attachment exists and is
// told it is not shared, rather than being handed a tap that silently fails.
//
// Consequence worth keeping in mind when changing this: a member's *upload* to a shared aircraft is
// denied too, so the client must not offer to attach files there either.
service firebase.storage {
  match /b/{bucket}/o {
    match /users/{userId}/{allPaths=**} {
      allow read, write: if request.auth != null && request.auth.uid == userId;
    }
  }
}
